{
  "texts": [
    "Where orthodoxy presents the relationship between part and whole as linear and hierarchical, where parts were simply components of a greater whole, the system approach looks at the presented relationship differently.",
    "For Luhmann in that sense, \"the system always reproduces itself by reducing complexity, that is, by selecting from a set of possibilities, and this selection process means that not all possibilities are realized.",
    "Hence, the sum of realized possibilities (the system) is always less than the total set of possibilities (its parts).\"",
    "Thus, when a distinction is observed, then it can be understood as the distinction of a system from its environment.",
    "For example, the scientific system operates through its internal mechanisms and structures, processing information according to its historically evolved internal logics and processes."
  ]
}